Association between cholesterol ration and health indicators

Shengxuan Wang

December 10, 2018

1 Introduction

In this study, I would like to study the association between cholesterol ratio and many health indicators, including BMI(body mass index), SBP(systolic blood pressure), DBP(Diastolic blood pressure), FPG(fasting plasma glucose), drinking and smoking status. Data were extracted from a computerized database established by the Rich Healthcare Group in China, which includes all medical records for participants who received a health check from 2010 to 2016.

3.2 Calculating the cho_ratio outcome

The cho_ratio outcome is measured by dividing the total cholesterol by the HDL.

RCdata <- RCdata %>%
  mutate(HDL_rc=ifelse(HDL==0,NA,HDL),
         cho_ratio = cholesterol/HDL_rc)

3.5 Filter people that are younger than 60 years old

I exclude people that are over 60 years old because older population usually have higher cholesterol levels comparing to other age groups. Include those older people may affect the model, so I exclude them.

RCdata <- RCdata %>%

4 The Code Book

Variable Type Description / Levels
sub_id Character subject code (1-100,322)
cho_ratio Quantitative dividing the total cholesterol by the HDL level
bmi Quantitative subject’s body-mass index
sbp Quantitative systolic blood pressure, in mm Hg
dbp Quantitative diastolic blood pressure, in mm Hg
fpg2 Quantitative fasting plasma glucose, in mmol/L
smoke_sta 3 level Cat. subject’s smoking status: never, past, current
drink_sta 3 level Cat. subject’s drinking status: never, past, current

5.2 Imputate quantative variables

For quantitative variables, I do imputation to take care those missing values. I use predictive mean matching approach to estimate the fpg2 values based on bmi. Estimate dbp based on bmi and fpg2. Estimate sbp based on bmi, fpg2, and dbp.

Variable NAs Class Imputation Approach Imputation Model Predictors
sbp 11 integer Predictive Mean Matching bmi, cho_ratio
dbp 11 integer Predictive Mean Matching bmi, cho_ratio
fpg2 6 numeric Predictive Mean Matching bmi, cho_ratio 
RC_imputed <- Study2_RCdata %>%
  impute_pmm(fpg2 ~ bmi) %>%
  impute_pmm(dbp ~ bmi + fpg2) %>%
  impute_pmm(sbp ~ bmi + fpg2 + dbp) 

colSums(is.na(RC_imputed))
       id    sub_id cho_ratio       bmi       sbp       dbp      fpg2 
        0         0         0         0         0         0         0 
smoke_sta drink_sta 
    71707     71707

5.3 Delete missing values in ‘smoke_sta’ and ‘drink_sta’

For the reason that these two categorical variables have too many missing values, and the data set contain 100299 subjects, so I just directly delete them.

RCfinal <- drop_na(RC_imputed, smoke_sta, drink_sta)

6 Step 2. Identify Training and Test Samples

Since the sample size of the data is really big, so I randomly select 4000 observations as training samples, and 2000 observations as test samples.

set.seed(20181210)
rc_training <- RCfinal %>% sample_n(4000)
rc_test <- RCfinal %>% sample_n(2000)
dim(rc_training)
[1] 4000    9
dim(rc_test)
[1] 2000    9

7 Step 3. Summarize the Outcome and Predictors

First I make three plots to visualize the distribution of the outcome in the training sample. Obviously the original outcome is right skewed. Then I make a transformation of logarithm of the outcome, now the distribution is approximately follow a normal distribution.

viz1 <- ggplot(rc_training, aes(x = "", y = cho_ratio)) +

viz2 <- ggplot(rc_training, aes(x = cho_ratio)) +

8.1 Collinearity Checking

Since the correlation between ‘sbp’ and ‘dbp’ is 0.701, which is very strong correlation. So I decide to drop sbp in my further study.

9 Step 5. Kitchen Sink Model Assessment

9.1 The kitchen sink model

I make a linear regression model to describe the relationship between log cho_ratio and five predictors, bmi, dbp, fpg2, smoke_sta, and drink_sta.

rc_ksink <- lm(log(cho_ratio) ~ bmi + dbp + fpg2 + smoke_sta + drink_sta, 
                data = rc_training)

9.2 Summary of the model

From the model, we can conclude that：

  1. This model accounts for 20.66% variation in the log of cho_ratio. The adjusted r square is similar to multiple r squared, so there is no problem with collinearity.

  2. The residual standard error is 0.23, so 95% of the prediction errors should be between -0.46 and 0.46, and all residuals should be between -0.69 and 0.69.

  3. The F test p value is very small, indicate that there is significant amour of predictive value can be accounted for the model.

9.3 Interpret coffiencient estimates

The equation of our model is : log(cho_ratio) = (0.42 + 0.03 bmi + 0.002 dbp + 0.02 fpg2 - 0.05 (if past smoker) or - 0.1 (if never smoker) + 0.01 (if past drinker) or + 0.05 (if never drinker))

This implies that for every 1 increase of bmi, we can expect an increase of 0.028 in the log cho_raio (90% confidence interval: 0.026, 0.030). If two subjects have same values except bmi, person a has a bmi of 20, and person b has a bmi of 30. Our model predicts that person a will have an increase of 0.28 in the log cho_ratio (90% confidence: 0.26, 0.3).

For other predictors:

  1. An increase of 1 mm Hg in dbp is associated with a significant increase of 0.002 (90% confidence interval:0.0010, 0.0022) in log cho_ratio.

  2. An increase of 1 mmol/L in fpg2 is associated with a significant increase of 0.02 (90% confidence interval:0.013, 0.034) in log cho_ratio.

  3. People who are past smoker will have an significant decrease of 0.05 (90% confidence interval:-0.08, -0.01) in log cho_ratio compared to current smoker.People who never smoke will have an significant decrease of 0.1 (90% confidence interval:-0.12, -0.09) in log cho_ratio compared to current smoker.

  4. People who are past drinker will have an non-significant increase of 0.01 (90% confidence interval:-0.03, 0.05) in log cho_ratio compared to current drinker.People who never drink will have an significant increase of 0.05 (90% confidence interval:0.009, 0.084) in log cho_ratio compared to current drinker.

cho_ratio = exp(0.42 + 0.0277 bmi + 0.002 dbp + 0.02 fpg2 -0.04 (if past smoker) or - 0.1 (if never smoker) +0.014 (if past drinker) or +0.034 (if never drinker))

If two subjects have same values except bmi, person a has a bmi of 20, and person b has a bmi of 30. For other predictors:

  1. An increase of 1 mm Hg in dbp is associated with a significant increase of 0.002 (90% confidence interval:0.0018, 0.0022) in log cho_ratio.

  2. An increase of 1 mmol/L in fpg2 is associated with a significant increase of 0.02 (90% confidence interval:0.016, 0.024) in log cho_ratio.

People who are past smoker will have an significant decrease of 0.04 (90% confidence interval:-0.060, -0.035) in log cho_ratio compared to current smoker.People who never smoke will have an significant decrease of 0.1 (90% confidence interval:-0.10, -0.09) in log cho_ratio compared to current smoker.

  4. People who are past drinker will have an non-significant increase of 0.014 (90% confidence interval:-0.001, 0.029) in log cho_ratio compared to current drinker.People who never drink will have an significant increase of 0.034 (90% confidence interval:0.019, 0.048) in log cho_ratio compared to current drinker.

Like previously mentioned, I exclude subject with id 58486, because of strange value of predictor. The p value is really small, so there is significant difference between the mean of log cho_ratio for the four groups. And ‘bmi’ account for 12% of the variance of log cho_ratio.

RCfinal <- RCfinal %>%
  mutate(log_cho = log(cho_ratio))
bmi_mod <- RCfinal %>% filter(id != "58486") %$%
  lm(log_cho ~ bmicat)
anova(bmi_mod)

14.5 Tukey’s Honestly Significant Differences approach

I would like to test the difference between each two groups. All the p values are close to 0, which indicates that the log cho_ratio is significantly different between each two groups.

TukeyHSD(aov(RCfinal$log_cho ~ RCfinal$bmicat), conf.level = 0.90)
